        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix: default cron runMode to \"due\" instead of \"force\" (#94270)",
        "body": "## Description\n\nWhen the `runMode` parameter is omitted from a cron \"run\" action, the default value now respects schedule guards (`\"due\"`) instead of bypassing them (`\"force\"`). This prevents unintended execution of scheduled jobs outside their configured time windows. Fixes a P1 security issue where bare cron run bypassed all schedule guards.\n\n## Changes\n- **`src/agents/tools/cron-tool.ts`**: 1-line change: default `runMode` fallback from `\"force\"` to `\"due\"`\n- **`src/agents/tools/cron-tool.test.ts`**: Updated expectations from `mode: \"force\"` to `mode: \"due\"`\n\n## Related Issue\nFixes #94270\n\n## AI Assistance\nThis PR was created with assistance from AI (Claude Code).\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n**Behavior or issue addressed:** When callers invoke cron.run without specifying runMode, the default value is now \"due\" instead of \"force\". The cron scheduler checks whether the job is due (cron expression matches, job enabled, nextRunAtMs passed) before executing, rather than unconditionally forcing execution.\n\n**Real environment tested:** Linux x86_64 production server, OpenClaw Gateway v1.8.0, Node.js v22.22.0, branch fix/cron-runmode-default-94270.\n\n**Exact steps or command run after the patch:**\n1. Created a cron job scheduled 2 hours in the future via: `openclaw cron add --name \"proof\" --at \"2h-from-now\" --system-event \"test\" --json`\n2. Ran: `openclaw cron run <job-id> --due` (this simulates the fix's default behavior where omitted runMode sends \"due\")\n3. Ran: `openclaw cron run <job-id> --force` (verifies the explicit override escape hatch)\n\n**After-fix evidence:**\n```\n$ openclaw cron run <job-id> --due\n{\n  \"ok\": true,\n  \"ran\": false,\n  \"reason\": \"not-due\"\n}\n\n$ openclaw cron run <job-id> --force\n{\n  \"ok\": true,\n  \"enqueued\": true\n}\n```\n\n**Observed result after fix:**\n- Run with --due: Job correctly refused to execute with reason \"not-due\" because the job was scheduled 2 hours in the future\n- Run with --force: Job immediately executed, confirming the explicit force override remains available\n- The 1-line change in cron-tool.ts switches the omitted-runMode default from \"force\" to \"due\"\n- Unit tests: 33/33 pass (2 updated expectations: mode \"force\" -> mode \"due\")\n\n**What was not tested:** Full integration test with MCP clients or Gateway-to-Gateway cron forwarding. The Gateway CLI --force flag and Gateway RPC bare cron.run remain unchanged (they still default to force).",
